&lt;p&gt;Please join the Harriman Institute for the opening reception of the exhibit &lt;em&gt;Children of the War&lt;/em&gt;&lt;em&gt;.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Children of the War&lt;/em&gt;&amp;nbsp;is organized around the publication of a new artist book by Marina T&amp;euml;mkina and Michel G&amp;eacute;rard titled&amp;nbsp;&lt;em&gt;Boys Fight&lt;/em&gt;. The text for this publication originated in 2014 in reaction to Russia&amp;rsquo;s initial invasion into Ukraine and was completed amid anxiety about the presidential election in the United States. The texts are written in the language of absurdity grounded in a feminist critique of the persistent presence of war. G&amp;eacute;rard&amp;rsquo;s drawings taken from the French dictionary&amp;nbsp;&lt;em&gt;Petit Larousse&lt;/em&gt;, published in Paris in 1942 during the Nazi Occupation, appear alongside T&amp;euml;mkina&amp;rsquo;s texts. The artist was a small child then and it was encouraging for him to look at the images of athletes playing traditional male sports. In imagery of fighting cavemen, fragmented dinosaurs, sportsmen, and combative games, G&amp;eacute;rard contends with the dissonance between play and violence, strength and growth, and word and image. These original drawings are presented at the Harriman Institute for the first time.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This exhibition focuses on the traumatic consequences of war for children&amp;rsquo;s psyches. What images and feelings does our conscience carry throughout life? Why do we, the children of the war and post-war period baby boomers, return to this experience of the family and collective traumas again and again? The exhibition includes T&amp;euml;mkina&amp;rsquo;s cycle of twelve texts &amp;ldquo;Children Who Starve&amp;rdquo; about the psychological self-negation as a result of food deprivation that children of the war experience.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The exhibit is co-organized with the&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href="https://www.russianamericanculture.com/"&gt;Russian American Cultural Center.&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;NYC PREMIERE&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;S&amp;eacute;bastien Lifshitz, 2024, Documentary, 104 min. In French with English subtitles&lt;br /&gt;
Screening followed by a Q&amp;amp;A with Sylvie Hofmann and Fanny Guex&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.eventbrite.com/e/screening-of-madame-hofmann-nyc-premiere-tickets-999292539887?aff=oddtdtcreator" target="_blank"&gt;REGISTER&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Sylvie has been a nurse for 40 years at the North Hospital of Marseille. Her life is running. Between patients, her sick mother, her husband and her daughter, she has always devoted her life to helping others. What if she decided to think a little about herself? To retire? Does she give herself the right, but above all, does she really want to retire?&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://youtu.be/STWkzOgycfM?si=Q9sfLAc01DCNnDVo" target="_blank"&gt;Trailer&lt;/a&gt;&amp;nbsp;(in French)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Sylvie Hofmann&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;has been a nurse since 1980 at the North Hospital of Marseille. She is a daughter, a wife, and a mother. Sylvie is now the new heroine of S&amp;eacute;bastien Lifshitz&amp;rsquo;s last documentary film. Lifshitz spent one year following her (in and outside the hospital) during the Covid pandemic.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Fanny Guex&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;is the Associate Director of the Columbia Maison Fran&amp;ccedil;aise.&lt;/p&gt;
