&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;The Society of Fellows hosts the Thursday Lecture Series (TLS), which runs regularly throughout the academic year. The Fall Semester TLS, our Fellows present their own work, chaired by Columbia faculty.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;On Postemancipation Coloniality: Narratives and Poetics from the Francosphere&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Lecture by&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href="https://sofheyman.org/persons/v%C3%A9ronique-charles"&gt;A. V&amp;eacute;ronique Charles&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
Chaired by&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href="https://sofheyman.org/persons/thomas-w-dodman"&gt;Thomas W. Dodman&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;During the first hundred years following legal emancipation across the French empire in 1848, in what ways did autobiographical narratives, prose fiction, and poetry address the continuation of black unfreedom? In this talk, A. V&amp;eacute;ronique Charles examines literary constructs of unfreedom within early twentieth-century Black literary production alongside bound fugitive slave narratives that circulated between Senegal and the metropole in the 1880s. This literary periodization specifically predates the institutional study of the respective fields of Caribbean and African literature. Charles notably charts a literary problem space through which readers can parse slavery&amp;rsquo;s past in canonical and lesser-known writings by Senegalese, Reunionese, and Antillean intellectuals, or &amp;eacute;volu&amp;eacute;s, whose citizenship dates back to nineteenth-century abolition.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;CU/ID holders, please register below.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
All others interested in attending, please email the SOF/Heyman at&amp;nbsp;sofheyman@columbia.edu&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h2&gt;WHINO restaurant and art gallery&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Ballston Quarter Mall&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Whatever the outcome of this historic election, you&amp;rsquo;ll likely feel glad that it is over for now! &amp;nbsp;Please join ColumbiaDC and our Ivy friends for a post-election happy hour!&amp;nbsp; All the polls are unanimous, sharing a drink and snacks with friends is always a win.&amp;nbsp; The first drink is on us to get the party started!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;WHINO is part art gallery and part restaurant and we are looking forward to sharing a refreshing evening with you! Perhaps these days more than others, let&amp;rsquo;s come together to reconnect, share, mix, and mingle!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.whinova.com/"&gt;WHINO&lt;/a&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;is located on the second floor of the Ballston Quarter mall, directly above True Foods Kitchen. They are between Macy&amp;#39;s and the bridge that leads to the Ballston Metro Station. If you are driving, it will be easiest to park in the Ballston Public Parking Garage, accessible from N Glebe Rd and N Randolph St, on the third floor (G3) of the garage, as that is the same level as where they are located.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Parking:&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;Public Parking lot available at the mall for only $1 (After 6pm) for the whole night.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Metro:&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;Ballston (Orange line)&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Lecture by Pritzker Prize winning architect&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;Eduardo Souto de Moura&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;on the work of Paulo Mendes da Rocha. Followed by a conversation with&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;Vanessa Grossman&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;(Penn) and&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;Mimi Hoang&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;(GSAPP, nArchitects), moderated by&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;Bart-Jan Polman&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;(GSAPP).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;From 1975 to 1979&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;Eduardo Souto de Moura&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;collaborated in the architectural practice of &amp;Aacute;lvaro Siza. From 1981 to 1991 he was assistant professor in his&amp;nbsp;&lt;em&gt;alma mater&lt;/em&gt;, and later began to work as professor in the Faculty of Architecture in the University of Porto. He has his own office since 1980.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;He has been visiting professor at the architectural schools of Paris-Belleville, Harvard, Dublin, ETH Zurich, Lausanne, Mendr&amp;iacute;sio and Mantova. He has participated in numerous seminars and given many lectures both in Portugal and abroad. His work has appeared in various publications and exhibitions. In 2001 he received the Heinrich-Tessenow-Medal in Gold, in 2011 the Pritzker Prize, in 2013 the Wolf Prize and in 2017 the Piranesi Prize. In 2018 he also received the award &amp;ldquo;Leone d&amp;rsquo;Oro&amp;rdquo; in La Biennale di Venezia. In 2019 he was awarded the &amp;ldquo;Arnold W. Brunner Memorial Prize 2019&amp;rdquo;, American Academy of Arts and Letters, New York, USA.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;This event is organized in collaboration with the Casa da Arquitectura in Porto, Portugal, in the context of the exhibition &amp;ldquo;Constructed Geographies: Paulo Mendes da Rocha / Paulo: Beyond Drawing.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
