&lt;h2&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Special Election Talk!&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;h2&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Where Did Trump Come From?:&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;strong&gt;Anti Democratic Movements and Illiberalism&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;h2&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Speaker: Steven Hahn, Pulitzer Prize Winner, Professor of History, New York University&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;h3&gt;Way before 2016. Steve Hahn, Pulitzer Prize-winning historian and author of the new Illiberal America, will trace its multi-century roots from the founding of the republic, through the 19th-century, and into the present. llliberalism, he argues, is not a deviation but a core impulse.&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;hr /&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Sponsored by the &lt;a href="https://www.publichealth.columbia.edu/research/centers/center-history-ethics-public-health" target="_blank"&gt;Center for the History and Ethics of Public Health&lt;/a&gt; and the &lt;a href="https://www.publichealth.columbia.edu/academics/departments/sociomedical-sciences" target="_blank"&gt;Department of Sociomedical Sciences&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Come together and&amp;nbsp;experience the stories, struggles and aspirations of the Lakota, M&amp;eacute;tis, Copts, and Jews and how we can inspire and support eachother. Our indigenous representatives&amp;nbsp;include activists and influencers&amp;nbsp;Lani Mekeel (Lakota/Jewish), Ryan Bellerose (M&amp;eacute;tis), Elisheva Ysabella Hazan (Jewish)&amp;nbsp;and Mariam Wahba (Copt).&amp;nbsp;The thousand year old sacred connection to a piece of land and the constant attempts of destruction and oppression, brings these people together in a discussion centered around pursuing common interests.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Food and Drinks will be provided!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Note: Please arrive 5-10 minutes early to take your seats so we can start on time and give the speakers the time and respect they need to share their stories.&lt;/p&gt;

